vision and perception was fundamentally called into question. Investigating this crisis of perception, Pauline Reid argues that the visual crisis that suffuses early modern English thought also imbricates sixteenth and seventeenth century print materials. These vision troubles in turn influenced how early modern books and readers interacted. Platonic, Aristotelian, and empirical models of sight vied with one another in a culture where vision had a tenuous relationship to external reality. Through situating early modern books’ design elements, such as woodcuts, engravings, page borders, and layouts, as important rhetorical components of the text, Reading by Design articulates how the early modern book responded to epistemological crises of perception and competing theories of sight.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aBooks and readingzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aBooks and readingzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aEarly printed bookszEnglandy16th century. 0aEarly printed bookszEnglandy17th century. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature publishingzEnglandy16th century. 0aLiterature publishingzEnglandy17th century. 0aVisual perceptionxHistoryy16th century. 0aVisual perceptionxHistoryy17th century. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh  aearly modern literature.  aepistemology.  ahistory of the book.  amedia.  anew materialism.  aphenomenology.  arhetoric.  avisuality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part